For the Attention of:
Subject:
Non−Disclosure Agreement
Date:
03 October 2022
Melior AI, Inc
600 N Broad Street, Suite 5 #3222
Middletown DE 19709+1032
UNITED STATES,
This confidentiality agreement (the “Agreement”) is made on 03 October 2022 between:
1.
Glennmont Asset Management Limited, an English limited liability company
(Company No. 09358843), having its registered office at 4th Floor, Reading Bridge
House, George Street, Reading, RG1 8LS (“Glennmont”), (which expression shall include its successors and assignees); and
2. Melior AI, Inc., a Delaware C−Corp with a Branch office in London, UK duly organised and existing under the laws of Delaware, United States of America, with registered number: EIN 37−1863225, whose registered office address is at 600 N Broad
Street, Suite 5 #3222
Middletown DE 19709+1032
UNITED STATES,
MELIOR AI UK (Branch Office)
UK Reg No. BR021269
3. (the “Company”), (which expression shall include its successors and assignees).
The Company and Glennmont may be referred to collectively herein as the “Parties” and
individually as a “Party”.
WHEREAS:
A. Glennmont and the Company have entered into discussions with each other in connection with Contract Intelligence (the “Project”).
B. In their discussions, Glennmont and the Company may wish to exchange certain
confidential or commercially sensitive information; and
The Parties hereby agree to the following:
1.
Definitions
In this Agreement:
"Advisors" means professional advisors advising the Receiving Party in relation to the
Project, including (unless the context otherwise requires) partners in and directors and
employees of such advisors;
“Confidential Information” means any confidential or proprietary information in any
form or medium, whether furnished orally or in writing; electronically delivered; tangible or intangible; or gathered by inspection and including (without limitation):
(i) 
all business, financial, commercially sensitive, operational, regulatory, technological, strategic or other information, processes or data of any kind including (without
limitation);
1
a. in the case of Glennmont, the Glennmont Information and all relations or correspondence with Customers, business partners or regulators;
b. software, source code, process flows, development methodologies, database
descriptions, processes, intellectual property and functionality descriptions relating to asset management and similar systems developed by or on behalf of
either Party;
c. 
all know−how, documentation and other information (in whatever format) relating to any of the works referred to above, and any related or similar works
and subject−matter;
d. any other information that is identified as being of a confidential or proprietary
nature; and
e. all copies, notes and records and all related information generated by the Receiving Party based on or arising out of any such disclosure;
“Customers” means any client or customer of any member of Glennmont;
"Data Protection Laws" means any applicable laws and regulations relating to the use or
processing of personal data including: (i) EU Regulation 2016/679 ("GDPR"); (ii) any
laws or regulations ratifying, implementing, adopting, supplementing or replacing the
GDPR (including, in the UK, the Data Protection Act 2018 ("DPA") and the applied GDPR
as defined in the DPA); and (iii) any laws and regulations implementing or made pursuant to EU Directive 2002/58/EC (as amended by 2009/136/EC) (including, in the UK,
the Privacy and Electronic Communications (EC Directive) Regulations 2003); in each
case, as updated, amended or replaced from time to time; and the terms "Data Subject",
"Personal Data", "processing", "processor" and "controller" shall have the meanings set
out in the GDPR;
“Disclosing Party” means the Party disclosing or owning the Confidential Information;
“Glennmont Information” means:
(i) 
software, source code, process flows, development methodologies, database descriptions, processes, intellectual property and functionality descriptions relating
to asset management and similar systems developed by or on behalf of Glennmont;
(ii) 
all know−how, documentation and other information (in whichever format) relating to any of the works referred to in paragraph (i) above, and any related or similar works and subject−matter; and
(iii) 
relations or correspondence between Glennmont and its Customers, business
partners or regulators;
"Non−Equivalent Country" means a country or territory other than (i) a member state of
the European Economic Area; or (ii) a country or territory which has at the relevant time
been decided by the European Commission in accordance with Data Protection Laws to
ensure an adequate level of protection for personal data;
“Owner” means the person who has disclosed Confidential Information to Glennmont;
“Purpose” means evaluating the Confidential Information (or part thereof) with a view
to negotiating with the other Party in relation to the Project;
“Receiving Party” means the Party receiving the Confidential Information;
"Representatives" means the directors, officers, potential lenders, employees and consultants of, and individuals seconded to work for, the Receiving Party.
2
2.
Non−Disclosure, Limited use and Data Protection
2.1 Each of the Parties hereto undertakes to the other that except and to the
extent otherwise provided or permitted in clause 3 of this Agreement it will:
(i) keep all Confidential Information secret and confidential;
(ii) not disclose the Confidential Information to anyone without prior written
consent of the other;
(iii) 
not use the Confidential Information for any purpose (including, but not limited
to, any competitive or commercial purpose) other than for the Purpose;
(iv) 
implement security practices against any unauthorised copying, use, disclosure
(whether that disclosure is oral, in writing or in any other form), access and damage or destruction; and
(v) 
promptly notify the other Party if it suspects or becomes aware of any unauthorised copying, use or disclosure in any form.
2.2 The Receiving Party will be under no obligation to keep confidential, and
clause 2.1 shall not apply to, any Confidential Information that it is able to
demonstrate:
(i) was in the lawful possession of the Receiving Party at the time of its disclosure by the Disclosing Party; or
(ii) after it is first disclosed to the Receiving Party, the Receiving Party lawfully receives the Confidential Information from a third party who does not
owe the Disclosing Party, or any of person connected with it, an obligation of
confidence in relation to it; or
(iii) is in the public domain at the time of disclosure, or has, after disclosure to
or acquisition by either Party, entered the public domain other than by reason
of a breach of the undertakings contained within this Agreement.
3.
Exceptions
3.1 The Receiving Party will be entitled to disclose any Confidential Information to its Representatives and Advisors who need to know such information
for the purposes of advising on the Project, provided that such Party will be
responsible for procuring their compliance with the terms of this Agreement
as if they were subject to the same obligations as each of the Parties hereto.
3.2 The Receiving Party will be entitled to disclose any Confidential Information if and to the extent that it is required to do so by any law or by any court
or regulatory agency or authority, provided that, to the extent that it is permitted to do so, the Receiving Party notifies the Disclosing Party as soon as possible upon becoming aware of any such requirement and it shall, as far as it is
practicable and lawful to do so consult the Disclosing Party to give the Disclosing Party an opportunity to contest the disclosure and then take into account the Disclosing Party’s reasonable requirements about the proposed
form, timing, nature and extent of the disclosure. If the Receiving Party is unable to consult with the Disclosing Party before disclosure is made pursuant
to this paragraph, the Receiving Party shall, to the extent not prohibited by
such applicable law, rule or requirement, inform the Disclosing Party of the
3
form, timing, nature and extent of the disclosure as soon as reasonably practicable after such disclosure is made.
4.
Returning Confidential Information
4.1 Following the termination of any discussions between the Parties relating
to the Project or either Party’s involvement with it or upon receipt of a written
request from the Disclosing Party, the Receiving Party will (subject to clause
4.2);
(i) promptly return to the Disclosing Party or, at its option, destroy all documents and all other materials (including computer media) or such parts
thereof as contain or reflect any Confidential Information, together with any
copies which are in the Receiving Party’s possession or control or are in the
possession or control of any of its directors, officers, servants, employees or
professional advisors to the extent that such information is in a form which is
capable of delivery or destruction;
(ii) promptly expunge all Confidential Information from any computer, word
processor, mobile telecommunications device or device similar to the foregoing into which it was programmed by or on behalf of that Party; and
(iii) if requested, provide certification to the Disclosing Party of compliance
with sub−clauses 4.1 (i) and (ii).
4.2 Notwithstanding clause 4.1, the Parties shall be permitted to retain:
(i) one copy of the Confidential Information for the purposes of and for so
long as required by any law, court or regulatory agency or authority; and
(ii) copies of any computer records and files containing any Confidential Information which has been created pursuant to its automatic archiving and
back−up procedures and which cannot be deleted.
3. Each Party acknowledges that neither the destruction nor return of any Confidential
Information nor the expunging of any of the same from any of the devices listed at
clause 4.1(ii) above or any other similar such devices will release it from the obligations contained in this Agreement.
5.
Rights in the Confidential Information
This Agreement does not confer upon the Receiving Party any right, license,
interest or title in or to the Confidential Information. No license is hereby
granted to the Receiving Party, by any legal rule or otherwise, to any rights of
the Disclosing Party and all title to the Confidential Information shall remain
vested solely in the Disclosing Party.
6.
Data Protection
If the Confidential Information includes Personal Data:
1. each of the Parties will only transfer Personal Data to the other in a Non−Equivalent
Country if the proposed transfer is made on the basis of an agreement, entered into
between the Disclosing Party and the Receiving Party, in an appropriate standard
form approved by the European Commission under Data Protection Law to adduce
appropriate safeguards in relation to the transfer of personal data to Non−Equivalent Countries, and the Receiving Party shall refrain from downloading any
4
accessible Personal Data from a Non−Equivalent Country until such an agreement is
put in place.
2. the Receiving Party shall abide by applicable Data Protection Law (including any applicable restrictions on international transfer) in respect of its processing of that Personal Data;
3. each Party shall not do, cause or permit to be done, anything which may result in a
breach by the other party of the Data Protection Laws; and
4. the Receiving Party shall promptly notify the Disclosing Party, with reasonable details, if that Personal Data is subject to any unauthorised (including accidental) disclosure or loss.
7.
Non−Solicitation of Employees
Each Party shall not, for 18 months from the date of this Agreement, directly or indirectly
solicit or endeavour to entice away any of the other Parties’ directors or senior employees
or financial salesmen, to join their company or any company of which they are a shareholder, or such companies’ subsidiaries or associates provided that neither Party shall be
prohibited from soliciting by means of a general advertisement which is not directed
specifically to such persons or by means of a search firm or employment agency provided
that such entities have not been instructed by either Party to specifically solicit employees
or officers of the other Party.
8.
Duration
The obligations of confidentiality of each Party under this Agreement will
continue for a period of 2 (two) years from the later of the date of this Agreement or, to the extent the document or material containing the Confidential
Information is marked “Confidential” or “Sensitive” and dated, from said
date. The provisions of clauses 7, 16 and 18 shall survive any termination of
the Agreement.
9.
Waiver
No failure or delay in exercising any right, power or privilege under this Agreement will
operate as a waiver of it, nor will any single or partial exercise of it preclude any other or
future exercise. No waiver of any provision of this Agreement shall be binding unless in
writing and signed by each of the Parties.
10.
Severability
The provisions of this Agreement shall be severable in the event that any of the provisions are held by a court of competent jurisdiction to be invalid, void or otherwise unenforceable and the remaining provisions shall remain enforceable to the fullest extent permitted by law. Any provision which is invalid, illegal or unenforceable shall, to the
fullest extent permitted by law, be deemed substituted by a provision that is valid, legal
or enforceable, and of which the operation and effect is as similar as possible to the provision that it substitutes.
11.
Limitation of Liability
The Disclosing Party (including its officers, employees, agents or advisors):
(i) does not make any express or implied representation or warranty as to the
accuracy or completeness of the Confidential Information; and
5
(ii) is not liable for direct or indirect damage arising in any way out of the use
of, or termination of the Receiving Party’s right to use, the Confidential Information.
12.
Damages as Inadequate Remedy
The Receiving Party acknowledges and agrees that monetary damages may
constitute an insufficient remedy for a breach or threatened breach of this
Agreement, and that the Disclosing Party shall be entitled to specific performance, injunctive or any other equitable relief as a remedy for a breach or
threatened breach. Such remedy shall not be deemed to be the exclusive remedy for the breach or threatened breach of this Agreement, but shall be in addition to all other remedies available to the Disclosing Party at law or in equity.
13.
Entire Agreement
This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and supersedes any oral statements, agreements or prior writings with respect hereto. This Agreement may be modified or amended only by a written agreement between the Parties. Neither
Party is relying upon any statement or conduct by the other in entering into
this Agreement.
14.
Obligations
No part of this Agreement shall constitute an obligation on either Party to enter into any
further agreements in relation to the Project.
15.
Assignment and Binding Effect
14.1 The obligations in this Agreement shall be binding upon and endure to
the benefit of the Parties and their respective successors and assigns. Neither
Party shall be entitled to assign the benefit (or part thereof) to any person
without the prior written consent of the other Party to this Agreement.
14.2 No agency, partnership or joint venture shall be deemed to be created between the Parties by virtue of this Agreement.
16.
Third Party Rights
A person who is not a Party to this Agreement shall have no rights under the Contracts
(Rights of Third Parties) Act 1999 to enforce any term of this Agreement except as follows:
(i) rights and benefits referred to in clauses 2, 4 and 10 may be enforced or relied on by any member of Glennmont, any owner of the Company or the
Owner; and
(ii) a person who is a permitted successor or assignee of the rights or benefits
of a party may enforce such rights or benefits,
and the Parties agree that no consent from the persons referred to in this clause is required for the Parties to vary or rescind this Agreement.
17.
Intellectual Property
6
Nothing in this Agreement is intended to grant a right or licence in relation to any intellectual property contained in or forming part of the Confidential Information.
18.
Governing Law
This Agreement shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of England and Wales and the Parties hereby submit to the exclusive jurisdiction of the English
Courts over any dispute arising out of or in connection with this Agreement.
IN WITNESS WHEREOF this Agreement has been duly executed by the Parties hereto
as of the date set out on the front page
Signed................................................. Signed.................................................
Signed for and on behalf of Glennmont Asset Management Limited,
Signed Martin Szyllo, CEO Signed.................................................
Signed for and on behalf of MELIOR AI, Inc.
